SUMMARY:Frontlines & Futures: Graduate Foreign Policy Salon Series: Refor
 ming the United Nations: Can Multilateral Governance Evolve?
DESCRIPTION:This session invites graduate students\, alumni\, faculty\, s
 taff\, and the general public to explore how the United Nations can evolv
 e in response to emerging global powers\, technological innovation\, and 
 shifting alliances. Participants will examine challenges like climate-ind
 uced migration\, artificial intelligence\, cyber threats\, and the rise o
 f new economic blocs\, assessing how these trends impact U.S. interests a
 nd global governance.  Through guided discussion\, reflection\, and visua
 l prompts\, participants will debate bold policy strategies\, consider et
 hical trade-offs\, and propose actionable reforms to strengthen multilate
 ral institutions. Questions will include: Which emerging trend or power c
 ould most reshape global politics? How should the U.S. respond to protect
  both national and global priorities? What bold policy steps could streng
 then multilateral governance\, and how can allies be coordinated to build
  trust? How should ethical principles guide decisions around emerging tec
 hnologies and global crises?  This safe\, structured space emphasizes can
 did dialogue\, critical thinking\, and real-world policy analysis. Lunch 
 will be provided. Join us for the final session of the academic year to s
 harpen your foreign policy instincts and engage with peers on the pressin
 g issues shaping tomorrow's global landscape.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p data-start="220" data-end="659">  This se
 ssion invites graduate students\, alumni\, faculty\, staff\, and the gene
 ral public to explore how the United Nations can evolve in response to em
 erging global powers\, technological innovation\, and shifting alliances.
  Participants will examine challenges like climate-induced migration\, ar
 tificial intelligence\, cyber threats\, and the rise of new economic bloc
 s\, assessing how these trends impact U.S. interests and global governanc
 e.</p><p data-start="661" data-end="1246">  Through guided discussion\, r
 eflection\, and visual prompts\, participants will debate bold policy str
 ategies\, consider ethical trade-offs\, and propose actionable reforms to
  strengthen multilateral institutions. Questions will include: Which emer
 ging trend or power could most reshape global politics? How should the U.
 S. respond to protect both national and global priorities? What bold poli
 cy steps could strengthen multilateral governance\, and how can allies be
  coordinated to build trust? How should ethical principles guide decision
 s around emerging technologies and global crises?</p><p data-start="1248"
  data-end="1552">  This safe\, structured space emphasizes candid dialogu
 e\, critical thinking\, and real-world policy analysis. Lunch will be pro
 vided. Join us for the final session of the academic year to sharpen your
  foreign policy instincts and engage with peers on the pressing issues sh
 aping tomorrow's global landscape.</p>
